data.title: Where are the stars of Carla Lane's Bread now?
data.meta_description: The Boswells enthralled viewers in the 1980s who loved the catchy theme tune, extra marital affairs and dining table rows. Here, FEMAIL looks at  where the stars of Bread are now.
data.text:
Fans of the hit Eighties series Bread, penned by Carla Lane, who passed away at the age of 87 have been sharing their memories from the cult Scouse comedy.

Set in the Liverpool neighbourhood of Dingle, Bread followed the ups and downs of the Boswell family, and was arguably Lane's finest television creation.

Airing for seven series between 1986 and 1991, the show centred around the dinner table in a working class household on Elswick Street - and the complicated love lives of those who gathered around it.

Scroll down for video

Mum's the word: Matriachal Nellie Boswell (Jean Boswell) offered her children tough love in Carla Lane's hit 1980s series Bread, which social media users have been remembering today

Today, social media site Twitter was awash with nostalgic tweets about everything from the catchy theme tune to the porcelain chicken basket that sat in the middle of the table.

@AntHatter wrote this morning: '...anyone else expect to be quietly & sadly humming the theme tune to 'Bread' all day?'

@Richard_Newbold felt similarly, saying: 'Anyone else got the theme tune to Bread going round in their head? #Earworm "Gotta get up, Gotta get out'"

For others, it was memories of the characters including Lilo Lill, the mistress of Freddie Boswell, that the sad news about Lane's death brought flooding back.

@JJOBuse wrote: '#CarlaLane #Bread was mint Joey, Lilo Lill 'She is a tart!', Grandad......brilliant.

@JFB1969 added: 'Sad to hear the passing of yet another great. RIP #CarlaLane and thanks for Lilo Lill'

Who was your favourite? Twitter user @Bateman1972 said he 'based his entire teenage years on our Adrian'

While the actors who starred in the show never quite reached household name status, some of them have gone on to have stellar careers including Jean Boht, who played matriarch Nellie Boswell, and Peter Howitt, who went on to star in and direct Hollywood films.

Here, FEMAIL digs deep and finds out exactly what happened to the stars behind Dingle's finest.

Thanks for Lilo Lill! Fans of the show have been sharing their favourite moments from Bread today

The orginal cast included actors Gilly Coman, Ronald Forfar, Jean Boht, Kenneth Waller, Nick Conway, Sharon Byatt, Rita Tushingham, Johnathan Morris, Charles Lawson and Peter Howitt

NELLIE BOSWELL - JEAN BOHT

In 2009, Jean starred in OAPz: A Hip Hop Comedy as part of the Camden Fringe Festival

Now 84, British actress Jean Boht appeared on television yesterday to share her memories of Lane.

Wirral-born Jean began her career in Some Mothers Do Ave Em in 1962 and enjoyed a string of high profile roles. The character of Nellie, the family matriarch, arguably defined her career.

It was a lucrative career, in September last year Boht put her eight-bedroomed home in Windsor up for sale for a cool 3.25million. She is married to New York-born composer Carl Davis and the couple have two daughters, one of whom is a director in Los Angeles.

Her most recent film role was in 2010, in the award-winning short Bad Night for the Blues.

FREDDIE BOSWELL - RONALD FORFAR

Nellie's wayward husband Freddie was permanently hen-pecked, not least about his relationship with 'that tart' Lilo Lill.

Ronald Forfar, now 76 and living in Chatham, Kent, has turned his hand to novel writing in recent years.

The wild hair and moustache sported by Freddie remains meaning that the actor still gets recognised by those who grew up with the show.

He told the Express last year: 'I still look similar to Freddie Boswell, so theres a reaction from people when they see me, but its a friendly reaction.

JOEY BOSWELL - PETER HOWITT

Mum's favourite! The smooth-talking Joey Boswell was a huge hit with female viewers of the show

Actor Peter Howitt was replaced by a less blonde Joey after just two years but for many, the original was the best. Nellie's favourite, Joey was cool, calm and almost always wearing a black leather jacket. Lane may have mischievously suggested that he was a male escort.

Actor Peter Howitt, now 59 and a dad of two, went on to carve out a career in Hollywood directing Sliding Doors and 2012 thriller Reasonable Doubt starring Dominic Cooper and Samuel L Jackson.

Actor Peter Howitt, who played Joey Boswell in the series paid tribute to Carla Lane earlier today

JACK BOSWELL - VICTOR MCGUIRE

As Jack Boswell, Victor McGuire, now 52, got his small screen big break in Bread and has gone to regularly appear on television and in UK theatre productions.

Goodnight Sweetheart followed as did a string of stage and film roles including n Peak Practice and Guy Ritchie's Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels.

ADRIAN BOSWELL - JONATHAN MORRIS

He was the most sensitive of the Boswell's with a delicate disposition and an eye for a nice suit.

The actor behind him, Lancashire-born Jonathan Morris, continued with mainly stage roles after Bread.

Now 55, Morris' career has faded somewhat with a 2005 appearance on reality television show The Games. He played the Jester in panto in Liverpool in 2013.

AVELINE BOSWELL - GILLY COLMAN/MELANIE HILL

Flame-haired Aveline was originally played by Gilly Coman until the 1988 Christmas special when she was replaced by Sunderland Melanie Hill.

The over-protected daughter was made to wear a whistle round her neck and aspired to be a vicar until marrying Protestant vicar Oswald.

Gilly Coman went on to appear in a string of soaps and TV shows including Coronation Street and Emmerdale but died from a heart attack in 2010 aged 54.

Melanie Hill, who's now 54, also played the girl-about-town and continues to enjoy a high-profile television career, most recently in BBC One school drama Waterloo Road and in the BBC's The Syndicate.

During the peak of her her Bread career she dated and married Sean Bean and the couple have two daughters, Lorna and Molly. They went on to divorce in 2007.

She's now a Coronation Street castmember and a regular guest on Loose Women.

BILLY BOSWELL - NICK CONWAY

The baby of the bunch, Billy Boswell, was the youngest and also the silliest, getting into scrapes aplenty with his lack of worldy wisdom. The actor who played him, Nick Conway, arguably peaked with the role. Now 51 Conway works as an actor, DJ and voiceover artist.

LILO LILL - EILEEN POLLOCK

In truth, Lilo Lill was little more than a bit part player in Bread, her presence the more impactful because of Nellie's extreme reaction to the mere mention of her name, which often evoked the response: 'She is a tart!'

Belfast-born actress Eileen Pollock, now 69, went on to star in Taggart and The Bill. She also took small parts in Irish film Angela's Ashes and Hollywood blockbuster Far and Away and has continued to work steadily.

GRANDAD - KENNETH WALLER

Is my tea ready? Kenneth Waller was the man behind Grandad, who was constantly asking about his dinner
